english:
  title: The Scholar's Tower
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A plum tree stands west of the Scholar's Tower, a hundred years or more,
    Its roots and trunk withered, branches and leaves grown thin—
    Yet by the pond, half its heart remains,
    And year after year it blooms with nature's intricate art.

    Among the flowers of the eastern garden, it spreads its canopy,
    Draped in faded green, bearing its ancient dignity.
    Three years I have recited verses with my friend,
    And Yu knows well what moves my heart.

    When spring's lord stirs all things to life,
    Why must he loose the wind to ravage and uproot?
    This slender, weathered frame cannot fight back—
    The blossoms fall to gutters, the tree topples sudden.

    I had just dried my tears for a child lost to death,
    Now this tree lies felled—how can I not grieve?
    Years ago I feared such a day would come,
    But fate's design—who could have known?

    Two saplings beside it I planted with my own hands,
    Yet though their branches spread, they wear no ancient grace.
    When will Yu return from the capital?
    Then perhaps his clear verses might sweep away this sorrow.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem was written as an elegy for an old plum tree that had stood by the Scholar's Tower for a century before being blown down by spring winds. The speaker had previously composed many poems about this tree with a friend named Yu (유자/克己). The tree's destruction becomes a meditation on mortality, loss, and the impermanence of all things—themes deepened by the poet's recent grief over the loss of his own child.
